in neovim, the harpoon plugin allows you to switch quickly between different lcoations in codebase. but seems marks allow same thing. what's the most modern/fast/best way to do this stuff?

The short answer is that Marks are for "where was I?" (state), while Harpoon is for "where am I going?" (intent).

In 2026, the ecosystem has matured past basic marks. While Harpoon remains the gold standard for "workflow-based" navigation, several modern alternatives offer more features or better performance.

1. The Distinction: Marks vs. Harpoon
Vim Marks (m[a-z]): These are great for jumping to a specific line in a specific file. However, they are hard to manage across projects, difficult to visualize, and require you to remember which letter corresponds to which file.

Harpoon: It treats your files as a pinned task list. You don't mark a line; you "harpoon" a file to a slot (1, 2, 3, 4). This allows for muscle-memory switching (e.g., <leader>1 for your component, <leader>2 for its styles) that persists and stays consistent as you work.

2. The Modern "Best" Ways (2026)
The Powerhouse: Grapple.nvim
If you like the idea of Harpoon but find it too limited, Grapple is the modern successor many are switching to.

Why it’s better: It supports scopes. You can have different sets of pinned files for different Git branches or projects.

Key Feature: It handles "tags" much more gracefully than Harpoon's UI and integrates natively with Telescope and modern statuslines.

The Minimalist Choice: Snacks.nvim (Picker/Explorer)
Created by folke, snacks.nvim has become the "all-in-one" utility for high-performance configs.

Modern Workflow: Instead of manually pinning files, many users now use the Snacks Picker for "Recent Files" or "Buffers." It’s so fast that the "mental overhead" of pinning a file with Harpoon is often slower than just fuzzy-finding the last 3 files you touched.

The Hybrid: Portal.nvim
If you find yourself jumping around but losing your place, Portal enhances the jumplist. It visually shows you where you're jumping to (like a more intelligent Ctrl-O / Ctrl-I), making "marks" feel obsolete because the jump history becomes searchable and visible.

3. Summary Comparison
Method	Best For...	Persistence	Complexity
Native Marks	Jumping within a single file/session.	Per-file	Low
Harpoon2	4-5 "core" files you switch between 100x a day.	Per-project	Medium
Grapple.nvim	Complex projects with multiple branches/contexts.	Per-branch	Medium
Telescope/Snacks	Finding any file in the project instantly.	Session-based	High (Config)
The "Best" Setup for 2026:
The most efficient modern workflow usually combines two things:

Fuzzy Finder (Telescope or Snacks): Use this for 90% of navigation.

Harpoon/Grapple: Use this for the 2-4 files you are currently editing to toggle between them instantly without typing a single search character.

Pro-tip: If you use Harpoon, map the UI to a very accessible key (like <C-e>) so you can reorder your "harpooned" files on the fly. This turns your navigation into a dynamic dashboard rather than a static list of marks.

