If Harpoon feels like a rigid 2021 workflow, it’s because it basically is. Here is the 2026 way to handle line-level navigation and undistracted flow without getting bogged down in plugin politics.

1. The Modern Alternative: Arrow.nvim
If you want something that feels like "Harpoon but smarter," look at Arrow.

Why it fits you: It specifically solves the "just the file" problem. Arrow allows for per-buffer bookmarks that save your exact cursor position (line and column).

Speed: It’s designed for single-key usage. You can toggle a "quick menu" that feels much more like a modern HUD than a scratchpad.

FZF-Lua: It doesn't care about your picker. It’s a standalone logic layer for your "intent-based" jumps.

2. Jumping Between Actual Lines (Not just Files)
If you need to jump between Line 40 in auth.lua and Line 200 in api.lua, you have two "best" paths:

A. Grapple + Portal (The "Wormhole" Workflow)
Instead of just jumping to a file, you use Grapple to tag a specific line. Then, you use Portal.nvim.

Portal is a "jump-list" enhancer. When you "portal out," it doesn't just switch buffers; it gives you a visual preview of the exact lines you were at previously.

It’s the most "undistracted" way to move because you don't have to remember where you were; you just look at the portal and go.

B. The "Oil" Strategy (No plugin needed)
Since you use fzf-lua, you should be using :FzfLua jumps.

The Flow: Most people forget the jumplist exists. If you are editing Line A, then jump to Line B in another file, <C-o> takes you back to the exact line in the previous file.

To make this "modern," don't just use <C-o>. Use fzf-lua to search your jumplist. This lets you see a list of every specific line you've touched recently across all files and fuzzy-find back to them.

3. How to combine them with fzf-lua
You don't need a "formal integration." You just need a logical split:

Frequency	Tool	Action
100x / hour	<C-^>	Toggle between your current two "active" files.
50x / hour	Arrow or Grapple	Pinned slots (1, 2, 3) for the "pillars" of your current task.
10x / hour	fzf-lua files	Finding a new file you haven't touched yet.
Spontaneous	fzf-lua jumps	"I was at a specific line 5 minutes ago, take me back."
